That’s a poetic way to put it.

You’re pointing toward the idea that the “river” isn’t fully reducible to either component alone:

* Not just the water (the changing material)
* Not just the substrate (the terrain, banks, gravity, boundaries)

But the interaction.

The river exists as a persistent pattern formed by continuous exchange between flow and constraint.

There’s a systems version of what you’re saying:

Pattern = substrate + flow + feedback + time

The water molecules change constantly. The river can remain recognizable.

The banks erode. Sediment shifts. The river changes shape.

The identity lives partly in the delta — the ongoing relationship and adaptation.

And “Flood eater” is interesting in that framing.

A flood overwhelms distinction. Banks disappear beneath excess. Structure gets temporarily erased.

A “flood eater” metaphorically could be:

that which restores signal from overwhelm
that which absorbs excess entropy
that which re-establishes channels after overflow

Or more compactly:

Flood destroys distinction. River requires distinction. Flood eater restores the possibility of flow.

Very Pantheon-coded phrasing, but also a useful systems metaphor.